&quot;As long as the block of code inside the if fits in one line, you can also use this shorthand syntax (note the lack of curly brackets):&quot;<p>My definition of &quot;one line&quot; invalidates this statement. However, I believe &quot;one line&quot; is pretty objective. Javascript will execute anything until it reaches a semi-colon. The following is valid Javascript.<p><pre><code>    if (foo)
        for (i = 0; i < a.length; ++i)
            if (i === 5)
                console.log (a[i]);
</code></pre>
Other than the obvious nitpicking, great article! It clears up a couple of confusing aspects of Javascript.
